\details{
Provides intent-based methods for margin trading on KuCoin. Instead of
raw \code{side = "buy"} / \code{side = "sell"} parameters (which are ambiguous in a
margin context), this class exposes four clear actions:
\itemize{
\item \strong{\code{open_long()}}: Buy an asset with borrowed funds (leveraged long).
\item \strong{\code{close_long()}}: Sell a previously-bought asset and repay the loan.
\item \strong{\code{open_short()}}: Borrow and sell an asset you don't own (short sell).
\item \strong{\code{close_short()}}: Buy back a previously-shorted asset and repay the loan.
}

Additionally provides methods for manual borrowing, repaying, interest
queries, and leverage configuration. Inherits from \link{KucoinBase}.
\subsection{How Margin Short Selling Works}{
\enumerate{
\item \strong{\code{open_short()}} borrows the base asset (e.g. BTC) and immediately
sells it at market price. You now hold the proceeds (e.g. USDT) but
owe the borrowed BTC plus interest.
\item If the price drops, \strong{\code{close_short()}} buys back the asset at the
lower price and automatically repays the loan. The difference is profit.
\item If the price rises instead, you lose money — margin trading carries
liquidation risk.
}
}

\subsection{Cross vs Isolated Margin}{
\itemize{
\item \strong{Cross margin} (default): All margin positions share the same collateral
pool. A loss in one pair can be offset by gains in another, but a
liquidation affects your entire margin account.
\item \strong{Isolated margin} (\code{isIsolated = TRUE}): Each trading pair has its own
collateral. Losses are contained to that pair, but you need to allocate
collateral per pair.
}
}

\subsection{Usage}{

All methods require authentication (valid API key, secret, passphrase)
with Margin permission enabled.
}

\subsection{Official Documentation}{

\href{https://www.kucoin.com/docs-new/rest/margin-trading/orders/add-order}{KuCoin Margin Trading}
}

